>Publishing package for OS/2 that runs even half as fast as Windows
>programs.

You're so ignorant.  FrameMaker, which most professionals consider to be the
premire desktop publishing package runs natively under OS/2.  Have you even
heard of FrameMaker?  Don't get it confused with that FrameMaker wannabe -
PageMaker.

>There are few Dos/Games that run under OS/2. You don't have a
>choice of apps for OS/2

Your choice of apps for OS/2 includes every Windows/DOS app out there.  That's
substancial.

>and you have very little choice of hardware.

Very little?  Name one major manufacturer that is not supported by OS/2?  There
are definitely some components that are marginally supported and some that are
completely not supported, but the majority of the most common pieces of
hardware are supported.  In many cases the Win3x versions of the drivers are
more mature than the OS/2 versions.  There are many instances where you can get
better resolution under Windows with a particular video card than under OS/2,
but Win95 also suffers from this problem.  How many Win95 users were suprised
(and bugged) to find out that Win95 supports their video card as advertised,
but only in 16 color VGA mode!?  After all that time and money, they downgraded
their video.

